In article &lt;1990May6.222815.13337@terminator.cc.umich.edu&gt; bryan@terminator.cc.umich.edu (Bryan Beecher) writes:
&gt;I just sent some mail to a few people today who either have caches
&gt;filled with more DTBs than LRNRs (Legit Root Ns Rrs) or haven't
&gt;updated their list of root nameservers in about three years.

I have been notifying the responsible parties whenever BIND logs a
response that lists the root name servers (DTB or LRNR) but shouldn't.
It indicates that someone's name server is misconfigured, and is causing
extra DNS traffic.

Now if I had a patch to BIND that logged the the occurances of when BIND
asks host A about X.Y.Z and host A replies with an empty answer section
but says the name servers for Y.Z are A and B, I could have even more
to do.
